SIMPLE: recognizance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Recognizance
<hw>Re*cog"ni*zance</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*k⟦ocr⟧g"n⟦icr⟧*z⟦ait⟧ns ⟦or⟧
r⟦esl⟧*k⟦ocr⟧n"⟦icr⟧-)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>reconnaissance</ets>, OF. <ets>recognoissance</ets>, fr.
<ets>recognoissant</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>recognoistre</ets> to
recognize, F. <ets>reconna⟦icir⟧tre</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>recognoscere</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- +
<ets>cognoscere</ets> to know. See <er>Cognizance</er>, <er>Know</er>,
and cf. <er>Recognize</er>, <er>Reconnoissance</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>recognisance</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An obligation of record entered into
before some court of record or magistrate duly authorized, with
condition to do some particular act, as to appear at the same or some
other court, to keep the peace, or pay a debt. A <ex>recognizance</ex>
differs from a <xex>bond</xex>, being witnessed by the record only, and
not by the party's seal.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The verdict of a jury
impaneled upon assize.</def> <rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Among lawyers the <xex>g</xex> in this and the related
words (except <xex>recognize</xex>) is usually silent.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A token; a symbol; a pledge; a badge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>recognizance</qex> and pledge of love⟦br⟧
Which I first gave her.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Acknowledgment of a person or thing; avowal;
profession; recognition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recognization</ent>⟦br⟧
